# Observability Standards

When writing or generating new service-layer code, include observability by default. Don't wait for a bug to add it.

## Metrics to add

For every new public service method or Lambda handler:

```ts
// Count invocations
metrics.increment('service.method_name.called', { partition, stage });

// Count outcomes
metrics.increment('service.method_name.success', { partition });
metrics.increment('service.method_name.error', { partition, error_type: err.name });

// Time external calls
const start = Date.now();
await externalCall();
metrics.timing('service.method_name.external_call_ms', Date.now() - start);
```

## Log context

Every log line in a service method should include relevant identifiers:

```ts
logger.info('Processing consent update', {
  userId,
  partition,
  purpose,
  operation: 'upsertConsent',
});
```

Don't log raw DynamoDB objects or full user records — log identifiers only.

## What to always log

- Entry point of a Lambda handler (with key input identifiers, never PII)
- Any external call (DynamoDB, SQS, external API) — before and after, or on failure
- Any branching decision that affects data (which path was taken and why)
- Errors with full context (don't just rethrow without logging)

## What NOT to log

- Full user preference records or consent values (PII risk)
- Passwords, tokens, keys
- High-cardinality values as metric tags (avoid logging individual userIds as tags)

## Flag for review

If generating code that skips observability due to unclear metric naming or missing context:
```ts
// TODO(observability): add metrics here — unclear what dimension to tag
```
